WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.480
I am Isabel Zimmerman, and I will be teaching about model explainability today.

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:19.480
I am a software engineer at Red Hat's Artificial Intelligence Center of Excellence with their

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:23.080
AIOps, so Artificial Intelligence Operations team.

00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:29.520
I'm also a very recent graduate from Florida Polytechnic University's Data Science program,

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:34.480
and of course, the most important personal tidbit, what was my pandemic hobby?

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:40.560
I've been spending hours as a homemade chemist to build the absolute perfect recipe for chocolate

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:41.560
chip cookies.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:46.279
So, in my everyday at work, I get to live the dream and play around with code and break

00:00:46.279 --> 00:00:51.720
code, and I get to spend a lot of time doing data science work as well.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:56.959
And I really stumbled upon this topic of model explainability actually when I was working

00:00:56.959 --> 00:00:57.959
as an intern.

00:00:57.959 --> 00:01:03.959
And it's just a topic that's stuck with me ever since, because people oftentimes think

00:01:03.959 --> 00:01:07.720
that machine learning answers all of our questions.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:13.879
But in reality, machine learning doesn't even have the same objectives as its users.

00:01:13.879 --> 00:01:19.919
We'll dive into this mismatch of objectives between models and humans, and we'll talk

00:01:19.919 --> 00:01:24.879
about how explainability helps to close this gap.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:29.760
But I also want everyone to be able to walk away from today being able to tell their colleagues

00:01:29.760 --> 00:01:33.080
about what explainability is and why you should be implementing it.

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:38.360
And I also want everyone to gain knowledge of just a few algorithms you can add into

00:01:38.360 --> 00:01:44.279
your own models and where you can add them into your machine learning workflow.

00:01:44.279 --> 00:01:49.160
So before we go any further, I think it's time to give you kind of the 30 second elevator

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:51.540
pitch for explainability.

00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:56.300
We know a machine learning model is just some sort of algorithm that uses an input

00:01:56.300 --> 00:02:03.459
of data, such as a cat picture, to give an output of some insight into that data, such

00:02:03.459 --> 00:02:06.580
as identifying the photo contents.

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:11.220
The output of the model really only answers the question of what.

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:14.580
In this example, what is this a photo of?

00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:17.059
A model will tell you that it's a cat.

00:02:17.059 --> 00:02:22.940
The output of the model told you the contents of the photo, but not the logic behind making

00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:25.779
the prediction.

00:02:25.779 --> 00:02:27.940
Explainability focuses on the why.

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:30.460
Why did this model say this was a cat?

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:34.880
Was it the eyes, the ears, the paws, the color?

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:40.419
So models look to optimize a mathematical function using the given data, and humans

00:02:40.419 --> 00:02:44.139
look to gain insight into their problems.

00:02:44.139 --> 00:02:49.779
At best, these two objectives align, but at worst, machine learning models make the

00:02:49.779 --> 00:02:55.820
front page news for unintended but really astonishing bias.

00:02:55.820 --> 00:03:00.500
Explainable machine learning is necessary to close this gap between the machine goal

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:04.979
of output and the human goal of understanding.

00:03:04.979 --> 00:03:08.940
And we need it when it's not enough to just get the prediction from your model.

00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:13.580
The model must also justify how it came to this prediction.

00:03:13.580 --> 00:03:19.619
Admittedly, I'm probably never going to convince you that explainability is important by showing

00:03:19.619 --> 00:03:21.839
you pictures of cats.

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:26.779
In fact, one of the most powerful reasons to use explainability is that it can help

00:03:26.779 --> 00:03:30.500
uncover bias and improve people's lives.

00:03:30.500 --> 00:03:36.179
So let's say a lender uses machine learning to determine someone's ability to pay back

00:03:36.179 --> 00:03:37.179
a loan.

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:43.460
If the lender is using a black box model, someone who is denied a loan may not be given

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:45.380
a reason why.

00:03:45.380 --> 00:03:50.619
This unknown reasoning is problematic because one, people will never know how they can change

00:03:50.619 --> 00:03:53.699
their habits to be approved for a loan.

00:03:53.699 --> 00:03:59.759
And two, it could be covering up this unintentional but harmful bias.

00:03:59.759 --> 00:04:03.860
So let's think about this entire workflow a little bit more carefully.

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:07.740
Here's your vanilla data science workflow.

00:04:07.740 --> 00:04:12.220
And we know that data science starts with having a well-defined problem.

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:15.100
And then you're going to gather your relevant data.

00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:19.540
You'll do some feature engineering to make sure you know what is all inside of it.

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:21.500
Maybe put it into a workable state.

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:23.179
You'll do some model tuning.

00:04:23.179 --> 00:04:24.820
And then we'll validate the model.

00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:28.899
And we're going to take a pause at this model validation step.

00:04:28.899 --> 00:04:34.500
Because in your validation step, you'll be looking at some sort of metric, such as root

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:40.459
mean squared error, or accuracy, or maybe precision or recall.

00:04:40.459 --> 00:04:44.339
And these help you know that your model is performing well.

00:04:44.339 --> 00:04:48.959
In our example, we'd be making sure that the cat model can robustly tell the difference

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:55.760
between cats and dogs or that the people who are getting loans are able to pay them off.

00:04:55.760 --> 00:05:01.519
After tuning, you'll deploy your model and continue to look at it to ensure that it continues

00:05:01.519 --> 00:05:06.279
to perform as expected, so that there's no data drift or any weird, strange things happening

00:05:06.279 --> 00:05:09.040
in the model once it's out in production.

00:05:09.040 --> 00:05:14.399
So this seems like a pretty well-rounded end-to-end machine learning workflow.

00:05:14.399 --> 00:05:17.839
Where does explainability fit in?

00:05:17.839 --> 00:05:23.320
And in general, explainability happens after a model has been validated.

00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:25.679
You can see there's really arrows all over.

00:05:25.679 --> 00:05:27.760
This is a process that's repeated many times.

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:32.399
You may have to go back to feature engineering, model training, model tuning, revalidate the

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:33.399
model.

00:05:33.399 --> 00:05:39.000
But you have to start with a model that is tuned and validated in order to have useful

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.739
explanations.

00:05:40.739 --> 00:05:45.600
I want to be very careful here, because I don't want people to think that you can add

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:51.140
an explainability algorithm rather than making a thoughtfully engineered model.

00:05:51.140 --> 00:05:56.820
You may have heard that if you put garbage data into a good model, you just have a garbage

00:05:56.820 --> 00:05:57.820
model.

00:05:57.820 --> 00:05:59.779
And the same principles apply here.

00:05:59.779 --> 00:06:04.100
A bad model will never give actionable explanations.

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:08.880
Model explainability does not fix poorly engineered models.

00:06:08.880 --> 00:06:12.920
It simply explains why decisions are being made.

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:18.859
But let's look at this workflow step by step, and we can see why models might need some

00:06:18.859 --> 00:06:21.660
more exploration with explanation.

00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:23.459
All right.

00:06:23.459 --> 00:06:25.420
So we're all data scientists here today.

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:29.959
And in this talk, we have our data science hat on, and we're looking at our data.

00:06:29.959 --> 00:06:33.700
We can kind of do a visual, you know, exploratory data analysis.

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:38.339
We see that the data is kind of all trending up and to the right.

00:06:38.339 --> 00:06:44.279
So we've done our bat, we understand our data, we can do some fake feature engineering looking

00:06:44.279 --> 00:06:46.019
at our data points here.

00:06:46.019 --> 00:06:50.700
And so now we're at our step where we're deciding which model to use.

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:55.339
And let's start off with the simplest algorithm we can.

00:06:55.339 --> 00:07:01.859
If you can recall your favorite middle school math teacher, hopefully y equals mx plus b

00:07:01.859 --> 00:07:03.420
rings a bell.

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:06.059
It's a classic.

00:07:06.059 --> 00:07:09.859
I'm going to take a moment to give a very important reminder.

00:07:09.859 --> 00:07:15.859
This is a reminder that machine learning is at its core just math.

00:07:15.859 --> 00:07:21.619
Sometimes we get so caught up with accuracy or whatever on their evaluation metrics,

00:07:21.619 --> 00:07:25.540
we forget what a model is, and it's just math.

00:07:25.540 --> 00:07:30.679
We can look at the options for fitting this model, and our thoughtfully engineered solution

00:07:30.679 --> 00:07:33.339
is the middle one.

00:07:33.339 --> 00:07:36.859
So we've trained and tested our algorithm with our data, and our algorithm is now our

00:07:36.859 --> 00:07:41.880
model y equals 5x plus 1, and it's best suited for our data set.

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:47.760
And we know that it's best suited for our data set because on a very basic level, it

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:52.079
minimized the average distance between each data point in the line.

00:07:52.079 --> 00:07:56.239
It was the line of best fit, it kind of goes in the middle of everything.

00:07:56.239 --> 00:07:57.880
We did a good job.

00:07:57.880 --> 00:07:59.760
And this is math we can interpret.

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:04.440
We can confidently look at our model and see that this is the best one.

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:06.200
And we can see why it's the best.

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:11.660
And we understand what happens to our prediction if we have different inputs.

00:08:12.440 --> 00:08:15.540
So we know that if we test a data point that's further to the right, we're probably going

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:17.540
to be getting a higher prediction.

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:20.980
And this is intuitive and it makes sense, especially when we have the graph right in

00:08:20.980 --> 00:08:21.980
front of us.

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:28.220
And it's a great example of a very interpretable model that doesn't need an explainability

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:32.059
algorithm for you to understand why it's making decisions.

00:08:32.059 --> 00:08:36.460
We can give ourselves all a pat on the back of being superstar data scientists right now

00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:41.900
because we 100% understand why this model is giving the output and how to manipulate

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:43.539
the inputs as well.

00:08:43.539 --> 00:08:48.400
And this is a really great and incredible moment and a win for us all as data scientists

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:55.679
until you realize that models really don't look like y equals 5x plus 1 in production.

00:08:55.679 --> 00:09:01.659
They might be part of a larger pipeline, or maybe they're just too complex to be understood

00:09:01.659 --> 00:09:03.460
at a glance.

00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:10.739
As our data sets grow in size and complexity, so does the math that makes up our model.

00:09:10.739 --> 00:09:17.299
And when this math is no longer as simple as y equals mx plus b, it can become difficult

00:09:17.299 --> 00:09:23.419
to interpret and explain how our model is working and why it's making decisions.

00:09:23.419 --> 00:09:28.340
And there are many different types of problems and many different types of models that can

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:30.539
really benefit from explainability.

00:09:30.859 --> 00:09:39.219
However, there is one type of model that especially benefits, and that's your black box models.

00:09:39.219 --> 00:09:45.700
In fact, this is probably the most important time to use explainability algorithms.

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:51.260
So black box models are models where you don't explicitly see how the variables of the model

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:55.059
are interacting with each other or just being used in general.

00:09:55.059 --> 00:09:59.799
They're fairly commonplace in industry since they're quite easy to implement and algorithms

00:09:59.799 --> 00:10:05.159
exist for nearly every type of machine learning problem that's needed to be solved, and they're

00:10:05.159 --> 00:10:07.380
fairly easy to implement.

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:12.320
But they can also be very dangerous, and I'll repeat that again to make sure it sits in.

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:17.359
Black box models can be very dangerous.

00:10:17.359 --> 00:10:22.700
When you don't know exactly how the model is creating predictions and you're solely

00:10:22.700 --> 00:10:28.520
relying on evaluation metrics like accuracy to determine if your model is doing well or

00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:34.960
not, it can be easy to have unintended consequences.

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:41.039
Some common household names for black box models are neural networks or gradient boosts

00:10:41.039 --> 00:10:42.979
or ensembles.

00:10:42.979 --> 00:10:49.520
These models give very high accuracy at the expense of not knowing their inner machinations.

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:54.599
Beyond your naturally occurring black box models, even some models that are technically

00:10:54.599 --> 00:10:58.419
interpretable are treated as black boxes.

00:10:58.419 --> 00:11:03.059
And that's because no data scientist is looking at, you know, a thousand different inputs

00:11:03.059 --> 00:11:10.179
into a random forest model, even though decision trees are classically labeled as interpretable

00:11:10.179 --> 00:11:11.340
models.

00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:16.820
Our problems and our data are getting more complex, and data scientists have to rely

00:11:16.820 --> 00:11:23.299
heavily on evaluation metrics such as our accuracy for model building.

00:11:23.299 --> 00:11:28.479
And we're once again reminded that a model and a human have different goals.

00:11:28.479 --> 00:11:30.979
Models want to optimize their math problem.

00:11:30.979 --> 00:11:33.859
Humans want to understand their human problem.

00:11:33.859 --> 00:11:39.539
For some industries, and especially highly regulated industries such as healthcare or

00:11:39.539 --> 00:11:44.179
financials, it's not enough to just get the prediction.

00:11:44.179 --> 00:11:50.140
The model must also justify how it came to the prediction.

00:11:50.140 --> 00:11:52.340
Explanations can help with this.

00:11:52.380 --> 00:11:57.659
Machine learning models can only be audited when they can be interpreted.

00:11:57.659 --> 00:12:01.500
Explanations can help with this, too.

00:12:01.500 --> 00:12:06.900
So to recap up until now, we know that machine learning models have a different goal than

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:08.119
humans.

00:12:08.119 --> 00:12:14.299
We know that explainability comes after thoughtfully engineered models, and we know that we need

00:12:14.299 --> 00:12:21.859
explainability because of the increasing complexity of models and the increasing use of black

00:12:21.859 --> 00:12:23.460
box models.

00:12:23.460 --> 00:12:27.260
So I'm not an explainability salesperson, even though it might sound like it, and I

00:12:27.260 --> 00:12:33.140
also want to make sure that you guys understand or you all understand that you do not need

00:12:33.140 --> 00:12:37.700
these every time you create a model.

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:41.280
First of all, not all models need explainability.

00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:42.539
Some models are simple.

00:12:42.539 --> 00:12:49.140
We saw this a few slides back in Y equals MX plus B. We don't need to add a complicated

00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:53.340
computational effort if it's just not needed.

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:59.059
If we have really robust feature engineering or if we have very in-depth subject matter

00:12:59.059 --> 00:13:06.739
expertise or if we just have a model that we can fully explain, it's not worth our time.

00:13:06.739 --> 00:13:09.739
There's another limitation in use cases.

00:13:09.739 --> 00:13:12.780
Not all use cases need explainability.

00:13:12.780 --> 00:13:18.219
In all honesty, sometimes you just don't care.

00:13:18.299 --> 00:13:24.099
This is most noticeable in some types of forecasting or times where the output just isn't really

00:13:24.099 --> 00:13:29.260
important enough to justify the added complexity of these algorithms.

00:13:29.260 --> 00:13:35.559
Additionally, there's some use cases where the problem is very well studied and feature

00:13:35.559 --> 00:13:39.619
interactions are just overall really well understood.

00:13:39.619 --> 00:13:43.500
And so explainability isn't needed there.

00:13:44.500 --> 00:13:51.539
Finally, you need to set very healthy boundaries with your explainability algorithms.

00:13:51.539 --> 00:13:57.219
Explanations help when you need to justify how a model came to a prediction.

00:13:57.219 --> 00:14:01.179
Explanations can expose bias.

00:14:01.179 --> 00:14:05.859
Explanations cannot fix biased models.

00:14:05.859 --> 00:14:10.140
They do not make changes to the underlying model or data.

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:14.460
So you need to really remember what explainability can and cannot do for you.

00:14:14.460 --> 00:14:16.299
All right.

00:14:16.299 --> 00:14:19.900
We've gone through our fine print for the limits of explainability, and it's time to

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:22.140
look at an application.

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:27.780
As a disclaimer, I don't work for a healthcare company, and I really don't claim to be giving

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:30.179
sound medical advice.

00:14:30.179 --> 00:14:34.219
But in my free time, I'm really interested in the world of healthcare and the hospital

00:14:34.219 --> 00:14:35.419
ecosystem.

00:14:35.419 --> 00:14:39.700
I think they have really interesting problems that can really benefit from machine learning

00:14:39.700 --> 00:14:41.140
especially.

00:14:41.140 --> 00:14:46.979
So I looked at this openly available sample data from MIMIC, which is de-identified patient

00:14:46.979 --> 00:14:50.359
data from a real hospital in the United States.

00:14:50.359 --> 00:14:56.760
I was particularly interested in better understanding healthcare acquired infections.

00:14:56.760 --> 00:15:01.380
And these are all infections that patients are not admitted with, but they contract from

00:15:01.380 --> 00:15:05.140
being in the healthcare environment, you know, just being in a hospital room and all the

00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:08.619
bacteria that's moving around in there.

00:15:08.619 --> 00:15:13.380
And I'm focusing in on one healthcare acquired infection called MRSA.

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:20.739
This data has a lot of inputs on patient demographics, such as age, gender, ethnicity, as well as

00:15:20.739 --> 00:15:27.299
medical information, such as symptoms, diagnosis, length of stay.

00:15:27.299 --> 00:15:31.820
I did a pretty vanilla feature engineering for this, and I made my model.

00:15:31.820 --> 00:15:34.119
It's a support vector classifier.

00:15:34.119 --> 00:15:41.960
And even though that the data set is unbalanced, it's about 90% accuracy, 90% accurate for

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:44.239
predicting MRSA.

00:15:44.239 --> 00:15:48.599
And we can say that my model is performing fairly well.

00:15:48.599 --> 00:15:52.599
And it could be, you know, in theory, ready to be in production, putting in production

00:15:52.599 --> 00:15:57.000
in quotes, because this is a fake in production moment.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:03.919
It's not a perfect example of a very big or highly complex data set or model.

00:16:03.919 --> 00:16:07.039
But this is our pseudo black box.

00:16:07.039 --> 00:16:12.479
The inputs are very wide, and I can't see exactly how the model is making these decisions.

00:16:12.479 --> 00:16:19.119
So it's a good contender for my actual absolute favorite use of explainers, which is the I'm

00:16:19.119 --> 00:16:22.599
just curious to see what's happening here usage.

00:16:22.599 --> 00:16:25.039
Curiosity can get you quite far.

00:16:25.039 --> 00:16:30.200
My next step in this problem is to look at the contending algorithms for explaining the

00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:32.440
prediction of these infections.

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:37.260
I do have to claim that all the examples I use in the next slides are fictitious and

00:16:37.260 --> 00:16:39.400
completely hypothetical.

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:43.799
But I want to look at this model at a few different levels.

00:16:43.799 --> 00:16:46.320
And the first level is at a global scope.

00:16:46.320 --> 00:16:52.460
This is kind of your 5,000 foot view of your model, understanding how the model itself

00:16:52.460 --> 00:16:54.520
is making decisions.

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:59.599
It can answer questions such as which features are important and what's the interaction between

00:16:59.599 --> 00:17:02.359
these features.

00:17:02.359 --> 00:17:04.719
Next we have our local scope.

00:17:04.719 --> 00:17:12.239
So this level of explainability is all about understanding how the model has made a decision

00:17:12.239 --> 00:17:14.560
for a particular instance.

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:19.520
There are many more local explainers than global explainers.

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:26.119
And that's partially because global explainers are very computationally complex and therefore

00:17:26.119 --> 00:17:30.599
very time consuming and very expensive to run.

00:17:30.599 --> 00:17:37.119
The lack of global explainers also exists because not all instances have the same weights

00:17:37.119 --> 00:17:38.680
for each feature.

00:17:38.680 --> 00:17:43.119
So we can't generalize individual explanations to the whole model.

00:17:43.119 --> 00:17:45.640
And that's kind of a mouthful to wrap your brain around.

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:52.239
So maybe a clearer way of saying this is in our healthcare frame of mind, not all patients

00:17:52.239 --> 00:17:54.260
come in with the same symptoms.

00:17:54.260 --> 00:17:59.280
You wouldn't want to generalize the symptoms of one patient to the entire hospital since

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:03.800
you would lose your ability to have a unique and accurate diagnosis.

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:05.579
The same idea applies here.

00:18:05.579 --> 00:18:11.380
You want to diagnose a particular instance and hope that looking at the smaller area

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:19.219
will give better results and explanations to other similar data points that you have.

00:18:19.219 --> 00:18:24.099
Local explainers can answer questions such as, you know, which features factored most

00:18:24.099 --> 00:18:27.099
heavily into this classification?

00:18:27.099 --> 00:18:32.859
And how would the prediction change if certain features changed?

00:18:32.859 --> 00:18:37.900
So I'll first look at some or a global explainability algorithm.

00:18:37.900 --> 00:18:44.660
As a reminder, this is your super high-level overview of how your model is giving predictions.

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:48.500
And the first algorithm we're looking at is called Shapley.

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:56.339
And the goal of Shapley is to explain the or I guess contribute the contribution of

00:18:56.339 --> 00:18:58.819
each feature to the model.

00:18:58.819 --> 00:19:03.420
So if we were looking at this graph here, your Shapley algorithm would give the output

00:19:03.420 --> 00:19:13.359
that globally higher Y values are light purple and higher X values are dark purple.

00:19:13.359 --> 00:19:19.859
In the very simplest terms, Shapley tells me what inputs are important and how important

00:19:19.859 --> 00:19:22.459
they are.

00:19:22.459 --> 00:19:24.540
So there's some pros and cons to Shapley.

00:19:24.540 --> 00:19:29.859
And the first pro that is really important is it's one of the few algorithms that can

00:19:29.859 --> 00:19:31.380
be used globally.

00:19:31.380 --> 00:19:36.020
Again, not many algorithms are able to be global.

00:19:36.020 --> 00:19:41.699
There is kind of like a hack because tree-based models are kind of fast.

00:19:41.699 --> 00:19:45.380
But if you're not wandering through a random forest, it's going to take a long time to

00:19:45.380 --> 00:19:47.020
train this.

00:19:47.020 --> 00:19:52.819
So I could see myself using Shapley to ask questions to my model such as, what are the

00:19:52.819 --> 00:19:57.219
most important features my model is using to predict MRSA?

00:19:57.219 --> 00:20:04.140
Would it be age, location of admission, or some sort of specific diagnosis?

00:20:04.140 --> 00:20:11.780
So if I'm looking for a less computationally expensive explainability algorithm, I might

00:20:11.780 --> 00:20:16.339
be looking into more local algorithms.

00:20:16.339 --> 00:20:23.260
And we'll look at a few different algorithms, but we're going to start at, and surprise,

00:20:23.260 --> 00:20:26.979
yay, Shapley values can also be used locally.

00:20:27.739 --> 00:20:33.300
The benefit of this approach is that local versions of this algorithm are a lot quicker.

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:39.739
But the negative side, hopefully, is that this is the number one favorite explainer

00:20:39.739 --> 00:20:42.939
for our evil data scientists.

00:20:42.939 --> 00:20:50.500
Research has shown that it is possible to hide bias in Shapley with adversarial attacks.

00:20:50.500 --> 00:20:57.180
This really isn't a big concern for those who are attempting to use this algorithm truthfully,

00:20:57.180 --> 00:21:02.180
but it could cause mistrust with interpreters of Shap explanations.

00:21:02.180 --> 00:21:06.099
You'd always have to walk into looking at a Shapley explanation with the possibility

00:21:06.099 --> 00:21:09.300
that it's fake in the back of your head.

00:21:09.300 --> 00:21:14.300
So whereas for the global Shapley explainer, I would see what features were most important

00:21:14.300 --> 00:21:20.099
for the model in general, or like the hospital in general, I can use local Shap to see what

00:21:20.099 --> 00:21:25.979
features were most important for a specific patient to be flagged as someone who would

00:21:25.979 --> 00:21:29.699
likely become MRSA positive.

00:21:29.699 --> 00:21:32.540
And again, Shapley is still kind of expensive to run.

00:21:32.540 --> 00:21:36.280
It's still computationally robust.

00:21:36.280 --> 00:21:42.300
So for those looking for a less computationally expensive technique, local interpretable model

00:21:42.300 --> 00:21:47.300
agnostic explanations, and that is such a mouthful, you understand why they shorten

00:21:47.300 --> 00:21:54.380
it to LIME, is an algorithm where you assume linearity around a particular instance and

00:21:54.380 --> 00:21:57.420
create a simpler model.

00:21:57.420 --> 00:22:03.780
The key intuition behind this one is that it's much easier to approximate a black box

00:22:03.780 --> 00:22:08.699
model by using a simple model locally in the neighborhood of the prediction we want to

00:22:08.699 --> 00:22:16.020
explain as opposed to trying to approximate the entire model globally.

00:22:16.020 --> 00:22:21.260
So it creates a local version of a linear model because Y equals MX plus B is the gift

00:22:21.260 --> 00:22:25.459
that your middle school teacher just keeps giving.

00:22:25.459 --> 00:22:28.180
In this case, it's our middle purple line.

00:22:28.180 --> 00:22:34.859
We might not have any idea of the equation for our red line, but we understand and can

00:22:34.859 --> 00:22:39.939
easily interpret Y equals 5X plus 1.

00:22:39.939 --> 00:22:45.859
And this is really a great moment for local explainability to be able to interpret this

00:22:45.859 --> 00:22:47.660
instance.

00:22:47.660 --> 00:22:52.180
LIME is also model agnostic, so it doesn't matter what your underlying model is.

00:22:52.180 --> 00:22:55.939
As long as you have a prediction function, LIME can be used.

00:22:55.939 --> 00:23:02.819
However, there is some danger in using LIME because you don't know how far this explanation

00:23:02.819 --> 00:23:04.000
holds.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:10.439
We can see that there's endpoints in this image, but the fit is not always as straightforward

00:23:10.439 --> 00:23:13.760
as this graph may lead you to believe.

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:20.239
There is fear that you can be overconfident in your explanations in LIME, and you could

00:23:20.239 --> 00:23:28.560
have misleading conclusions for unseen but similar instances.

00:23:28.560 --> 00:23:31.280
Anchors actually work a lot like LIME.

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:36.319
They both proxy local behavior of the model in a linear way.

00:23:36.319 --> 00:23:43.280
But remember that LIME broke because we didn't know to what extent the explanation held up.

00:23:43.280 --> 00:23:48.199
And anchor kind of steps up to the plate and incorporates coverage.

00:23:48.199 --> 00:23:56.760
I like to think of this coverage as going from a one-dimensional line in LIME to a two-dimensional

00:23:56.760 --> 00:24:03.619
area, which we can see since our small purple line has turned into a more robust rectangle

00:24:03.619 --> 00:24:06.719
that's implementing coverage.

00:24:06.719 --> 00:24:13.599
Anchors explain individual predictions of any black box classification model by finding

00:24:13.599 --> 00:24:22.219
a decision rule or set of features or range of features that anchors the prediction sufficiently.

00:24:22.219 --> 00:24:30.219
So everything that's within this light purple rectangle would be classified as light purple.

00:24:30.219 --> 00:24:35.699
Anchors main selling point is that they address the shortcomings of LIME.

00:24:35.699 --> 00:24:41.420
But the boundaries are still approximate and occasionally don't even exist, in which case

00:24:41.420 --> 00:24:47.300
anchors become no different than LIME, and they still carry the same pros and cons.

00:24:47.300 --> 00:24:53.699
In the context of my MRSA exploration, I could see myself using anchors to see what

00:24:53.699 --> 00:24:59.819
ranges of different features factor into a MRSA positive prediction.

00:24:59.819 --> 00:25:07.819
For example, an anchor might be able to tell me that the output is like ages 20 to 30 are

00:25:07.819 --> 00:25:13.420
at a 20% risk of contraction.

00:25:13.420 --> 00:25:20.260
So LIME, SHAP, and anchors all look at what features are important and look at interpretable

00:25:20.260 --> 00:25:23.199
models for a particular data point.

00:25:23.199 --> 00:25:29.099
But contrastive explanation methods kind of shift gears and focus more on cause and effect.

00:25:29.099 --> 00:25:35.739
So you can test how your model output can be changed for each instance.

00:25:35.739 --> 00:25:41.680
Contrastive explanation methods focus on explaining instances in terms of pertinent positives

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:44.160
and pertinent negatives.

00:25:44.160 --> 00:25:49.219
Pertinent positives refer to features that should be minimally and sufficiently present

00:25:49.219 --> 00:25:53.800
to predict the same class as the original instance.

00:25:53.800 --> 00:26:01.000
And pertinent negatives identify which features should be minimally and necessarily absent

00:26:01.000 --> 00:26:05.800
from the instance in order to maintain the original prediction class.

00:26:05.800 --> 00:26:13.119
Kind of a mouthful, but humans really think in contrastive explanation methods naturally.

00:26:13.119 --> 00:26:17.920
If I was trying to get my partner to locate me at a restaurant, I might say that I have

00:26:17.920 --> 00:26:21.199
a hat on, but I'm not wearing red.

00:26:21.199 --> 00:26:26.719
If I wanted to have an explanation for this graph, my CEM algorithm would tell me that

00:26:26.719 --> 00:26:36.400
the star is light purple because Y is greater than 10, but X is less than 12.

00:26:36.400 --> 00:26:42.800
While CEM is useful for human understanding, they get less useful when the classes aren't

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:43.800
similar.

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:45.280
And this is kind of intuitive.

00:26:45.280 --> 00:26:52.339
You can distinguish clear yet subtle differences between a cat and a dog, but the differences

00:26:52.339 --> 00:26:58.219
between a cat and the flu are so numerous that it doesn't even seem logical to list

00:26:58.219 --> 00:26:59.780
them all out.

00:26:59.780 --> 00:27:07.380
If my CEM output is that all people who contract MRSA are admitted through the emergency room,

00:27:07.380 --> 00:27:13.140
but did not show signs of respiratory distress, the location would be a pertinent positive

00:27:13.140 --> 00:27:18.699
and symptoms would be a pertinent negative.

00:27:18.699 --> 00:27:24.500
Counterfactual explanation is the minimum possible change required to generate the desired

00:27:24.500 --> 00:27:25.579
output.

00:27:25.579 --> 00:27:30.140
So kind of think if X had not occurred, Y would not have occurred.

00:27:30.140 --> 00:27:36.619
In our example here, if I wanted to change my light purple classification to dark purple,

00:27:36.619 --> 00:27:42.560
the star would have had to move down at least that set amount.

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:48.500
On the positive side, counterfactuals don't require access to the data or even the model.

00:27:48.500 --> 00:27:52.180
They only need the predict function to generate outputs.

00:27:52.180 --> 00:27:56.540
But the cons for counterfactuals are similar to CEMs.

00:27:56.540 --> 00:28:00.900
Oftentimes there are so many ways to change the output.

00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:05.060
In fact, there's so many ways to change the output that it's no longer useful to list

00:28:05.060 --> 00:28:06.939
all of them out.

00:28:06.939 --> 00:28:12.880
A counterfactual that I might uncover with a patient is maybe someone who was admitted

00:28:12.880 --> 00:28:17.699
through the emergency room would not have acquired an infection if they had entered

00:28:17.699 --> 00:28:22.020
through urgent care instead.

